N.Y. / Region

Bond With Past Foe Is Fodder for Attack on Cuomo

By DAVID M. HALBFINGEROCT. 14, 2010



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Andrew M. Cuomo, the Democratic nominee for New York governor, on Thursday. He has profited from his personal and professional ties to Andrew L. Farkas.

Credit
            Michael Nagle for The New York Times        



Perhaps no man would become more important to Andrew M. Cuomo’s political and personal finances than the real estate magnate Andrew L. Farkas.But in 1997 the two men were sworn enemies.Mr. Cuomo, then the nation’s housing secretary, was pursuing a case in which Mr. Farkas’s company had paid millions of dollars in kickbacks to a landlord. Mr. Farkas believed that his company, Insignia Financial Group, was being unfairly singled out for what had been a widespread and accepted industry practice.Eventually, Mr. Cuomo settled the case, clearing the way for  Insignia  to complete the sale of its apartment business for $910 million in 1998. And three years later, he began a friendship with Mr. Farkas, astonishing Insignia’s workers who had lived through the battle.That relationship proved hugely beneficial to both men.Mr. Cuomo received hundreds of thousands of dollars for his campaigns, and, in a three-year stretch between political races, a job working for Mr. Farkas that paid him more than $2.5 million.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Farkas, having made an ally of his onetime nemesis, gained new prestige as he pursued ventures from the West Village to the United Arab Emirates. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Now, as Mr. Cuomo runs for governor on a pledge to clean up Albany, the relationship is drawing renewed fire.Mr. Cuomo’s Republican opponent, Carl P. Paladino, suggests Mr. Farkas essentially repaid Mr. Cuomo  for going easy on his company in the case with the Department of Housing and Urban Development.“Here’s a man who stole millions of dollars, and Andrew gives him a pass,”  Mr. Paladino said on a radio show this week.Mr. Cuomo brushes off the charge, saying the idea that he, HUD officials and the Justice Department conspired to give Mr. Farkas a pass  in exchange for personal rewards for Mr. Cuomo much later is preposterous. And there is little evidence to support it.But the subject remains delicate enough that Mr. Cuomo declined repeated requests to be interviewed about it, and his unabashed reliance on Mr. Farkas stands out in a time in which Mr. Cuomo scrupulously seeks to avoid even the appearance of controversy.Mr. Farkas, in a telephone interview, said that befriending Mr. Cuomo back in 2001 required overcoming his own deep suspicion and anger. And he said he had taken  a big role in Mr. Cuomo’s career knowing full well how it might look.“The truth is, there’s a friendship here, a love and a respect here, and a bond, that surmounts all of this stuff,” Mr. Farkas said. “Because there is nothing about all of this noise that is remotely inappropriate or improper.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Farkas likened their 2001 détente to the wary peacemaking of two old warriors.But in 1997, he and Mr. Cuomo were more like crown princes of the housing world. Mr. Farkas, the heir to the Alexander’s department store fortune, had spent years amassing apartment portfolios, building Insignia into the nation’s largest owner and manager of multifamily property. Mr. Cuomo had just taken over at HUD, with promises to clean up fraud and waste.In a  campaign with the Justice Department, Mr. Cuomo authorized a  lawsuit against A. Bruce Rozet, a notorious HUD landlord, accusing him of taking kickbacks from the management company he had hired to run his buildings. Insignia had taken over that management company, and continued the arrangement, turning over one-third of its HUD fees to Mr. Rozet.Insignia was not named as a defendant in the lawsuit, but the allegation that it had broken the law by splitting its fees inflamed Mr. Farkas and threatened his company. “The finger was being pointed directly at Farkas, and the charge was led by Cuomo,” said a former Insignia executive. “It couldn’t have gotten more personal.”
Photo






Andrew L. Farkas, in 2005, a period when he employed Andrew M. Cuomo, whom years earlier was a sworn enemy. Mr. Farkas is now finance chairman in Mr. Cuomo’s campaign for governor.

Credit
            Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times        


Insignia settled in 1998, paying a total of $7.4 million — the government had alleged $7.6 million in kickbacks — and providing evidence against Mr. Rozet. The former executive said Insignia feared that the government could otherwise bar  it from handling HUD properties, a crippling blow.A prosecutor in the case, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said Insignia had received no special treatment; rather, HUD and the Justice Department were less aggressive with Insignia than with Mr. Rozet because Insignia had inherited the fee-splitting arrangement and because of a lack of  evidence that it had intended to break the law.But Mr. Farkas was deeply embittered toward Mr. Cuomo.It was not until the summer of 2001 that the two men actually met; Mr. Farkas happened to be in the office of a friend when Mr. Cuomo arrived to talk about his run for governor.
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


