Manage Email Preferences
Not you?
Privacy Policy
Opt out or contact us anytime




As Mr. Farkas sat there, seething, he recalled, Mr. Cuomo realized who he was and asked for a meeting.“I figured I’d never see or hear from the man again,” Mr. Farkas said. But when he returned to his office, he found a message from Mr. Cuomo.The two had a long, intense conversation. Mr. Farkas complained that HUD had mistreated his company and that the case was “terribly disruptive” and meritless. Mr. Cuomo asked to put their past differences behind them, but Mr. Farkas insisted that he also talk  with Insignia’s managers and directors. Again, Mr. Cuomo surprised him by doing so, earning “mixed reviews,” Mr. Farkas said.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

But Mr. Farkas was impressed, and increasingly, enamored of Mr. Cuomo. He was still new to politics, and was “a little scared of it,” but he began helping Mr. Cuomo with fund-raising. Then Mr. Cuomo’s father, former Gov. Mario M. Cuomo,  asked him to serve as Andrew’s finance chairman.Mr. Farkas said it was he who broached their adversarial past, asking: “What are people going to say? People love to make allegations about things. Are you concerned?’ And they said, ‘No, we’ve thought about it; we’re not concerned.’ ”The turnabout staggered workers at Insignia, who bridled at requests to contribute to Mr. Cuomo. Said one executive: “In the beginning a lot of us on the inside had a hard time taking that relationship seriously.”Mr. Cuomo’s run for governor in 2002 failed, and the next year, he found himself in the midst of a difficult divorce. Mr. Farkas, having made another fortune amassing and selling Insignia’s commercial real estate business, was building up a new venture, Island Capital, and offered Mr. Cuomo a job.Mr. Cuomo’s title was vice president. He helped in both big-picture and small-bore ways, offering political advice, mediating disputes and counseling Mr. Farkas on dealing with foreign governments.In one case, Mr. Cuomo got Mr. Farkas to listen to opponents of a luxury marina planned for the Virgin Islands, which would have restricted access to the bay for public-housing tenants who lived across the street. And he helped broker a deal in which Mr. Farkas sold the West Village Houses, a subsidized complex in Manhattan, to the tenants. Mr. Farkas said Mr. Cuomo persuaded him to accept a lower price than he could have exacted to avoid a public battle that “would not be good for the man I wanted to be.”Mr. Cuomo did not treat his job as a sinecure; colleagues and adversaries called him diligent and astute. But by 2005, eyeing a run for attorney general, he began spending more time preparing for that campaign, associates said.In May 2006, a wealthier Mr. Cuomo left Island Capital to campaign full time. Mr. Farkas said he agreed to serve as Mr. Cuomo’s finance chairman again, but reminded Mr. Cuomo to expect more attacks over their adversarial past.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

“Are we O.K. with that?” Mr. Farkas said he asked.“We’re fine with it,” he said Mr. Cuomo told him.Mr. Farkas said he understood why their relationship was  viewed with suspicion. But he insisted his motives were pure, saying he was not seeking any personal gain.“I need this kind of thing like I need a hole in my head,” he said. “There’s nothing in this for me. I do this purely out of love for the man, and because the future of this state is important to my family.”
Continue reading the main story






